Let’s chat.

One of the questions I still get to this day is why I dress up so much. It’s the classic “but no one is going to see you”. And that’s exactly it, it doesn’t matter if someone sees me or not because it’s never EVER about others. Getting dressed, doing my hair and makeup is a form of self care for me. It makes me feel beautiful and confident. If I take the time to go to the gym and make myself wholesome meals, why wouldn’t I do it for the rest of my body.

We have to trust we know what’s best for ourselves, and we have to be confident in our decisions. I had someone tell me I made them feel bad because they were wearing sweats to work from home. But if sweats is what makes you feel beautiful then trust in your decision and wear it confidently. What I do shouldn’t matter. And if you don’t feel good in it then change it. I wear what I wear because it’s the thing that makes me get up everyday and be motivated to work. We have to trust that we know what’s best for ourselves.

Arrived at the beautiful town of St Andrews, Scotland. After about 2 minutes of unpacking we immediately headed out and explored the town. I love history, I couldn’t help myself.

St Andrews Cathedral was built around 1130 and was one of the first places of worship for the citizens of St. Andrews. The Church took 150 years to be completed. The beautiful Cathedral saw the end of its time during the reformation in 1559 when the church was destroyed and eventually abandoned.

Over the years there was talk of restoring the cathedral but by the 1600’s the Cathedral instead became a provider of building materials for other St Andrews development. This is something that happened quite a lot with Cathedral throughout the reformation. Its one of the main reasons for why there are so many ruins scattered throughout the UK.

I’ve always appreciated medieval architecture, there’s a beauty in it that is just simply does not exist today. A beauty that requires time, patience, and care. Do you all prefer modern or more historic architecture? Tell me your favourite architecture style.

The sense of calmness here has made me realize how fast life moves in North America. No time to think or even take in the little moments. I’ve caught myself watching less movies, using my headphones less, and just being more present than ever before. It’s made me realize how much I’ve been on autopilot. I’ve been going through life, the routine, checking off the checklist, but forgetting to just be present and look up. Have you experienced this?

Let’s chat. I need your thoughts! 

This trip I’ve been focusing more on photography. Capturing the beautiful moments and details of life. With that I’ve noticed how “fast” social media has gotten and I’ve realized how much I enjoy photos as apposed to videos. It’s allowed me to slow down, look, take it in, and read. As apposed to a quick video. What are your thoughts? Do you prefer photos or videos? Are you getting tired of short form content? 

Over the last months (maybe longer) I’ve attached further and further from these short form videos. It feels as if you always have to be snappy, loud, funny. To me this feel disingenuous for me. I want the full explanation, I want calmness, not chaos. What do you think?

I felt the need to share with you all that there is a street named Butts Wind in St Andrews and it still makes me giggle. What’s the silliest street name you’ve ever heard? I think this one takes the cake for me😂

I thought I’d start a new Monday series sharing new makeup and skincare bits and my thoughts on them! Although the way I apply my makeup remains the same simply changing a product can make the world of a difference so I thought I’d share my thoughts on new bits! So let’s start!

Mascara: @lancomeofficial Lash I’Dole. This reminds me of the glossier mascara but at a affordable price point. It gives that natural defined look without being clumpy. Also washes off easily which is always a selling point for me 👌🏼

A new series where I share my thoughts on some new products I’ve been trying out!

Face Cream: @lamer I’ve been using this cream for a while now and here are my thoughts. You need a pea sized amount which is a bit different to other creams where I feel the need to use more and this go through the product a bit quicker. Blush: @diorbeauty rosy flow blush in mahogany. This is the newest shade in Diors blush range and one that I think it’s brilliant. For our Monday makeup and skincare I wanted to be adventurous and do a full face of @cledepeaubeaute in the hopes of discovering some new favourites. Foundation: Radiant Cream Foundation. I am almost exclusively a skin tint girl so for me to say that I like a foundation kind of shocks me. Mascara: Perfect Lash Mascara. This will without a doubt give you perfect lashes. The moment I put this on I actually ran out of the room to show my lashes to someone. It gives voluminous lashes without a single clump. It’s astonishing. 1000/10 for me.

Last summer I stumbled into a shop in Paris and discovered @santamarianovella1221 A perfumery with roots that date all the way back to 1221, Florence. Founded within the gardens carefully grown by the Friars of the Santa Maria Convent, S. M Novella became what we now know as a beautiful perfumery. It wasn’t only the history of the brand that caught my attention, but the timeless packaging and feel of the fragrances. It gives you a stopped in time feeling, and in a world where everything is racing towards modernity, I love a little moment in time. 

I have a very strong belief that fragrances have no gender. Being someone that loves woody, smokey, and elegant fragrances, (often associated with men’s fragrances) I love being able to walk into a shop and not be bound by the “women’s section”. Within the boutiques you’ll notice all the bottles are equally beautiful, leaving you with one choice, the fragrance that feels good to you.

A classic loafer. Yes or No?👀

We all now the famous “penny loader” but did you know that it was @ghbass that was the first to introduce the Penny Loafer to the world? Founded in 1876, the brand has truly stood the test of time. 

Loafers were a traditional Norwegian farm shoe intended for “loafing around the fields” but it was Bass that took the shoe and put a stylish spin on them, creating what we now know as the Penny Loafer. Over the years Bass has stayed rooted in their classic and timeless designs, something I personally admire. With so many loafers on the market it was Bass that felt like the right choice. A classic design mixed with a beautiful high quality.

Let’s Chat. What are your thoughts on disclosing partnerships when it comes to content creators/influencers? Do like disclosure? Is it important to you? Does it create trust? Tell me all your thoughts. 

If you’re new here, Let’s Chat is a time for me to chat with you and have real conversations about something I feel passionate about. Outside of social media something that fuels me are challenging conversations and debates. I love getting passionate and in turn growing and learning as an individual. So every once in a while I like to bring that part of me here. So let’s chat. 

Disclosure is something that from the start has been something I prioritized. I am so far from perfect but it’s something that I work at every single day. I think a lot of the distrust towards the influencer world comes from dishonesty or the assumption of dishonesty. Which as a creator myself I completely understand. Although I can’t create trust across the board, I can create trust in my little corner of the world, right here. And so 2 years ago I decided to share everything from Brand Partnerships and PR Gifts (two things which are required to be disclosed by the Canadian Ad Guidelines) to PR Services (a service that has been partially or fully covered) and PR Stays (a fully or partially covered stay at a hotel, resort, etc) in the hopes of creating a transparent and honest space. Because from the start my goal was to share things that I love and feel passionate about!

What are your thoughts? What else would you like disclosed? Leave me all your thoughts and questions.❤️
